[src:garch-models/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] The ARCH model is appropriate when the error variance in a time series follows an autoregressive (AR) model; if an autoregressive moving average (ARMA) model is assumed for the error variance, the model is a **generalized autoregressive conditional heteroskedasticity** (**GARCH**) model.
[src:garch-models/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] ARCH models are commonly employed in modeling financial time series that exhibit time-varying volatility and volatility clustering, i.e. periods of swings interspersed with periods of relative calm (this is, when the time series exhibits heteroskedasticity).
[src:garch-models/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] ARCH-type models are sometimes considered to be in the family of stochastic volatility models, although this is strictly incorrect since at time *t* the volatility is completely predetermined (deterministic) given previous values.
[src:garch-models/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] To model a time series using an ARCH process, let $~\epsilon _{t}~$ denote the error terms (return residuals, with respect to a mean process), i.e. the series terms.
[src:garch-models/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] The random variable $z_{t}$ is a strong white noise process.
[src:garch-models/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] An ARCH(*q*) model can be estimated using ordinary least squares.
[src:garch-models/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] A method for testing whether the residuals $\epsilon _{t}$ exhibit time-varying heteroskedasticity using the Lagrange multiplier test was proposed by Engle (1982).
[src:garch-models/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] Obtain the squares of the error ${\hat {\epsilon }}^{2}$ and regress them on a constant and *q* lagged values: ${\hat {\epsilon }}_{t}^{2}=\alpha _{0}+\sum _{i=1}^{q}\alpha _{i}{\hat {\epsilon }}_{t-i}^{2}$ where *q* is the length of ARCH lags.
[src:garch-models/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] The null hypothesis is that, in the absence of ARCH components, we have $\alpha _{i}=0$ for all $i=1,\cdots ,q$ .
[src:garch-models/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] The alternative hypothesis is that, in the presence of ARCH components, at least one of the estimated $\alpha _{i}$ coefficients must be significant.
[src:garch-models/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] In a sample of *T* residuals under the null hypothesis of no ARCH errors, the test statistic *T'R²* follows $\chi ^{2}$ distribution with *q* degrees of freedom, where $T'$ is the number of equations in the model which fits the residuals vs the lags (i.e. $T'=T-q$ ).
[src:garch-models/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] If *T'R²* is greater than the Chi-square table value, we *reject* the null hypothesis and conclude there is an ARCH effect in the ARMA model.
[src:garch-models/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] If *T'R²* is smaller than the Chi-square table value, we do not reject the null hypothesis.
[src:garch-models/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] If an autoregressive moving average (ARMA) model is assumed for the error variance, the model is a generalized autoregressive conditional heteroskedasticity (GARCH) model.
[src:garch-models/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] Generally, when testing for heteroskedasticity in econometric models, the best test is the White test.
[src:garch-models/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] However, when dealing with time series data, this means to test for ARCH and GARCH errors.
[src:garch-models/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] Exponentially weighted moving average (EWMA) is an alternative model in a separate class of exponential smoothing models.
[src:garch-models/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] As an alternative to GARCH modelling it has some attractive properties such as a greater weight upon more recent observations, but also drawbacks such as an arbitrary decay factor that introduces subjectivity into the estimation.
[src:garch-models/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] The asymptotic, that is for large samples, standard deviation of $\rho (i)$ is $1/{\sqrt {T}}$ .
[src:garch-models/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] Individual values that are larger than this indicate GARCH errors.
[src:garch-models/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] To estimate the total number of lags, use the Ljung–Box test until the value of these are less than, say, 10% significant.
[src:garch-models/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] The Ljung–Box Q-statistic follows $\chi ^{2}$ distribution with *n* degrees of freedom if the squared residuals $\epsilon _{t}^{2}$ are uncorrelated.
[src:garch-models/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] It is recommended to consider up to T/4 values of *n*.
[src:garch-models/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] The null hypothesis states that there are no ARCH or GARCH errors.
[src:garch-models/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] Rejecting the null thus means that such errors exist in the conditional variance.
[src:garch-models/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] , which ensures the non-negativity and stationarity of the variance process.
[src:garch-models/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] For stock returns, parameter $~\theta$ is usually estimated to be positive; in this case, it reflects a phenomenon commonly referred to as the "leverage effect", signifying that negative returns increase future volatility by a larger amount than positive returns of the same magnitude.
[src:garch-models/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] This model should not be confused with the NARCH model, together with the NGARCH extension, introduced by Higgins and Bera in 1992.
[src:garch-models/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] Integrated Generalized Autoregressive Conditional heteroskedasticity (IGARCH) is a restricted version of the GARCH model, where the persistent parameters sum up to one, and imports a unit root in the GARCH process.
[src:garch-models/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] The exponential generalized autoregressive conditional heteroskedastic (EGARCH) model by Nelson & Cao (1991) is another form of the GARCH model.
[src:garch-models/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] where $g(Z_{t})=\theta Z_{t}+\lambda (|Z_{t}|-E(|Z_{t}|))$ , $\sigma _{t}^{2}$ is the conditional variance, $\omega$ , $\beta$ , $\alpha$ , $\theta$ and $\lambda$ are coefficients. $Z_{t}$ may be a standard normal variable or come from a generalized error distribution.
[src:garch-models/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] The formulation for $g(Z_{t})$ allows the sign and the magnitude of $Z_{t}$ to have separate effects on the volatility.
[src:garch-models/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] This is particularly useful in an asset pricing context.
[src:garch-models/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] Since $\log \sigma _{t}^{2}$ may be negative, there are no sign restrictions for the parameters.
[src:garch-models/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] The GARCH-in-mean (GARCH-M) model adds a heteroskedasticity term into the mean equation.
[src:garch-models/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] The Quadratic GARCH (QGARCH) model by Sentana (1995) is used to model asymmetric effects of positive and negative shocks.
[src:garch-models/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] Similar to QGARCH, the Glosten-Jagannathan-Runkle GARCH (GJR-GARCH) model by Glosten, Jagannathan and Runkle (1993) also models asymmetry in the ARCH process.
[src:garch-models/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] The Threshold GARCH (TGARCH) model by Zakoian (1994) is similar to GJR GARCH.
[src:garch-models/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] Hentschel's **fGARCH** model, also known as **Family GARCH**, is an omnibus model that nests a variety of other popular symmetric and asymmetric GARCH models including APARCH, GJR, AVGARCH, NGARCH, etc.
[src:garch-models/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] In 2004, Claudia Klüppelberg, Alexander Lindner and Ross Maller proposed a continuous-time generalization of the discrete-time GARCH(1,1) process.
[src:garch-models/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] is the purely discontinuous part of the quadratic variation process of L .
[src:garch-models/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] where the positive parameters $\beta$ , $\eta$ and $\varphi$ are determined by $\alpha _{0}$ , $\alpha _{1}$ and $\beta _{1}$ .
[src:garch-models/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] Now given some initial condition $(G_{0},\sigma _{0}^{2})$ , the system above has a pathwise unique solution $(G_{t},\sigma _{t}^{2})_{t\geq 0}$ which is then called the continuous-time GARCH (**COGARCH**) model.
[src:garch-models/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] The multiplicative factor multi-frequency GARCH (MF2-GARCH) was proposed by Conrad and Engle (2025), and it features stationary returns and allows for recursive long-term volatility forecasts.
[src:garch-models/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] They exploit the fact that daily standardized volatility forecast errors of one-component GARCH models are essentially unpredictable based on past daily standardized forecast errors, but a rolling window moving average of past daily standardized forecast errors does have predictive power.
[src:garch-models/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] Empirically, the long-term volatility component is closely linked to news about macroeconomics and monetary policy.
[src:garch-models/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] The immediate reaction of stock market indices to U.S. macroeconomic announcements (e.g., initial jobless claims or incoming orders) depends on the level of long-term stock market volatility.
[src:garch-models/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] The ZD-GARCH model does not require $~\alpha _{1}+~\beta _{1}=1$ , and hence it nests the Exponentially weighted moving average (EWMA) model in "RiskMetrics".
[src:garch-models/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] Since $~\omega =0$ , the ZD-GARCH model is always non-stationary, and its statistical inference methods are quite different from those for the classical GARCH model.
[src:garch-models/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] Based on the historical data, the parameters $~\alpha _{1}$ and $~\beta _{1}$ can be estimated by the generalized QMLE method.
[src:garch-models/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] Spatial GARCH processes by Otto, Schmid and Garthoff (2018) are considered as the spatial equivalent to the temporal generalized autoregressive conditional heteroscedasticity (GARCH) models.
[src:garch-models/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] In contrast to the temporal ARCH model, in which the distribution is known given the full information set for the prior periods, the distribution is not straightforward in the spatial and spatiotemporal setting due to the contemporaneous dependence between neighboring spatial locations.
[src:garch-models/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] where $~s_{i}$ denotes the i -th spatial location and $~w_{iv}$ refers to the $iv$ -th entry of a spatial weight matrix and $w_{ii}=0$ for $~i=1,...,n$ .
[src:garch-models/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] The spatial weight matrix defines which locations are considered to be adjacent.
[src:garch-models/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] In spatiotemporal extensions, the conditional variance is modelled as a joint function of spatially lagged past squared observations and temporally lagged volatilities, allowing for both cross-sectional and serial dependence.
[src:garch-models/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] These models have been applied in fields such as environmental statistics, regional economics, and financial econometrics, where shocks can propagate over space and time.
[src:garch-models/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] Recent reviews summarise methodological developments, estimation techniques, and applications across disciplines.
[src:garch-models/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] In a different vein, the machine learning community has proposed the use of Gaussian process regression models to obtain a GARCH scheme.
[src:garch-models/conditional-variance] In probability theory and statistics, a **conditional variance** is the variance of a random variable given the value(s) of one or more other variables.
[src:garch-models/conditional-variance] Particularly in econometrics, the conditional variance is also known as the **scedastic function** or **skedastic function**.
[src:garch-models/conditional-variance] Conditional variances are important parts of autoregressive conditional heteroskedasticity (ARCH) models.
[src:garch-models/conditional-variance] The conditional variance tells us how much variance is left if we use $\operatorname {E} (Y\mid X)$ to "predict" *Y*.
[src:garch-models/conditional-variance] Here, as usual, $\operatorname {E} (Y\mid X)$ stands for the conditional expectation of *Y* given *X*, which we may recall, is a random variable itself (a function of *X*, determined up to probability one).
[src:garch-models/conditional-variance] As a result, $\operatorname {Var} (Y\mid X)$ itself is a random variable (and is a function of *X*).
[src:garch-models/conditional-variance] Recall that variance is the expected squared deviation between a random variable (say, *Y*) and its expected value.
[src:garch-models/conditional-variance] The expected value can be thought of as a reasonable prediction of the outcomes of the random experiment (in particular, the expected value is the best constant prediction when predictions are assessed by expected squared prediction error).
[src:garch-models/conditional-variance] Thus, one interpretation of variance is that it gives the smallest possible expected squared prediction error.
[src:garch-models/conditional-variance] If we have the knowledge of another random variable (*X*) that we can use to predict *Y*, we can potentially use this knowledge to reduce the expected squared error.
[src:garch-models/conditional-variance] As it turns out, the best prediction of *Y* given *X* is the conditional expectation.
[src:garch-models/conditional-variance] By selecting $f(X)=\operatorname {E} (Y|X)$ , the second, nonnegative term becomes zero, showing the claim.
[src:garch-models/conditional-variance] Here, the second equality used the law of total expectation.
[src:garch-models/conditional-variance] We also see that the expected conditional variance of *Y* given *X* shows up as the irreducible error of predicting *Y* given only the knowledge of *X*.
[src:garch-models/conditional-variance] where recall that $\operatorname {E} (Z\mid X=x)$ is the conditional expectation of *Z* given that *X=x*, which is well-defined for $x\in S$ .
[src:garch-models/conditional-variance] Note that here $\operatorname {Var} (Y|X=x)$ defines a constant for possible values of *x*, and in particular, $\operatorname {Var} (Y|X=x)$ , is *not* a random variable.
[src:garch-models/conditional-variance] The connection of this definition to $\operatorname {Var} (Y|X)$ is as follows: Let *S* be as above and define the function $v:S\to \mathbb {R}$ as $v(x)=\operatorname {Var} (Y|X=x)$ .
[src:garch-models/conditional-variance] Then, $v(X)=\operatorname {Var} (Y|X)$ almost surely.
[src:garch-models/conditional-variance] The "conditional expectation of *Y* given *X=x*" can also be defined more generally using the conditional distribution of *Y* given *X* (this exists in this case, as both here *X* and *Y* are real-valued).
[src:garch-models/conditional-variance] This can, of course, be specialized to when *Y* is discrete itself (replacing the integrals with sums), and also when the conditional density of *Y* given *X=x* with respect to some underlying distribution exists.
[src:garch-models/conditional-variance] In words: the variance of *Y* is the sum of the expected conditional variance of *Y* given *X* and the variance of the conditional expectation of *Y* given *X*.
[src:garch-models/conditional-variance] The first term captures the variation left after "using *X* to predict *Y*", while the second term captures the variation due to the mean of the prediction of *Y* due to the randomness of *X*.
[src:garch-models/heteroscedasticity] In statistics, a sequence of random variables is **homoscedastic** (/ˌhoʊmoʊskəˈdæstɪk/) if all its random variables have the same finite variance; this is also known as **homogeneity of variance**.
[src:garch-models/heteroscedasticity] The complementary notion is called **heteroscedasticity**, also known as **heterogeneity of variance**.
[src:garch-models/heteroscedasticity] The term originates from the Ancient Greek σκεδάννυμι *skedánnymi*, 'to scatter'.
[src:garch-models/heteroscedasticity] Assuming a variable is homoscedastic when in reality it is heteroscedastic (/ˌhɛtəroʊskəˈdæstɪk/) results in unbiased but inefficient point estimates and in biased estimates of standard errors, and may result in overestimating the goodness of fit as measured by the Pearson coefficient.
[src:garch-models/heteroscedasticity] The existence of heteroscedasticity is a major concern in regression analysis and the analysis of variance, as it invalidates statistical tests of significance which assume that the modelling errors all have the same variance.
[src:garch-models/heteroscedasticity] While the ordinary least squares (OLS) estimator is still unbiased in the presence of heteroscedasticity, it is inefficient and inference based on the assumption of homoskedasticity is misleading.
[src:garch-models/heteroscedasticity] In that case, generalized least squares (GLS) was frequently used in the past.
[src:garch-models/heteroscedasticity] Nowadays, standard practice in econometrics is to include heteroskedasticity-consistent standard errors instead of using GLS, as GLS can exhibit strong bias in small samples if the actual skedastic function is unknown.
[src:garch-models/heteroscedasticity] Because heteroscedasticity concerns expectations of the second moment of the errors, its presence is referred to as misspecification of the second order.
[src:garch-models/heteroscedasticity] The econometrician Robert Engle was awarded the 2003 Nobel Memorial Prize for Economics for his studies on regression analysis in the presence of heteroscedasticity, which led to his formulation of the autoregressive conditional heteroscedasticity (ARCH) modeling technique.
[src:garch-models/heteroscedasticity] Consider the linear regression equation $y_{i}=x_{i}\beta _{i}+\varepsilon _{i},\ i=1,\ldots ,N,$ where the dependent random variable $y_{i}$ equals the deterministic variable $x_{i}$ times coefficient $\beta _{i}$ plus a random disturbance term $\varepsilon _{i}$ that has mean zero.
[src:garch-models/heteroscedasticity] The disturbances are homoscedastic if the variance of $\varepsilon _{i}$ is a constant $\sigma ^{2}$ ; otherwise, they are heteroscedastic.
[src:garch-models/heteroscedasticity] In particular, the disturbances are heteroscedastic if the variance of $\varepsilon _{i}$ depends on i or on the value of $x_{i}$ .
[src:garch-models/heteroscedasticity] One way they might be heteroscedastic is if $\sigma _{i}^{2}=x_{i}\sigma ^{2}$ (an example of a scedastic function), so the variance is proportional to the value of x .
[src:garch-models/heteroscedasticity] More generally, if the variance-covariance matrix of disturbance $\varepsilon _{i}$ across i has a nonconstant diagonal, the disturbance is heteroscedastic.
[src:garch-models/heteroscedasticity] The matrices below are covariances when there are just three observations across time.
[src:garch-models/heteroscedasticity] The disturbance in matrix A is homoscedastic; this is the simple case where OLS is the best linear unbiased estimator.
[src:garch-models/heteroscedasticity] The disturbances in matrices B and C are heteroscedastic.
[src:garch-models/heteroscedasticity] In matrix B, the variance is time-varying, increasing steadily across time; in matrix C, the variance depends on the value of x .
[src:garch-models/heteroscedasticity] The disturbance in matrix D is homoscedastic because the diagonal variances are constant, even though the off-diagonal covariances are non-zero and ordinary least squares is inefficient for a different reason: serial correlation.
[src:garch-models/heteroscedasticity] Heteroscedasticity often occurs when there is a large difference among the sizes of the observations.
[src:garch-models/heteroscedasticity] A classic example of heteroscedasticity is that of income versus expenditure on meals.
[src:garch-models/heteroscedasticity] A wealthy person may eat inexpensive food sometimes and expensive food at other times.
[src:garch-models/heteroscedasticity] A poor person will almost always eat inexpensive food.
[src:garch-models/heteroscedasticity] Therefore, people with higher incomes exhibit greater variability in expenditures on food.
[src:garch-models/heteroscedasticity] At a rocket launch, an observer measures the distance traveled by the rocket once per second.
[src:garch-models/heteroscedasticity] In the first couple of seconds, the measurements may be accurate to the nearest centimeter.
[src:garch-models/heteroscedasticity] After five minutes, the accuracy of the measurements may be good only to 100 m, because of the increased distance, atmospheric distortion, and a variety of other factors.
[src:garch-models/heteroscedasticity] So the measurements of distance may exhibit heteroscedasticity.
[src:garch-models/heteroscedasticity] One of the assumptions of the classical linear regression model is that there is no heteroscedasticity.
[src:garch-models/heteroscedasticity] Breaking this assumption means that the Gauss–Markov theorem does not apply, meaning that OLS estimators are not the Best Linear Unbiased Estimators (BLUE) and their variance is not the lowest of all other unbiased estimators.
[src:garch-models/heteroscedasticity] Heteroscedasticity does *not* cause ordinary least squares coefficient estimates to be biased, although it can cause ordinary least squares estimates of the variance (and, thus, standard errors) of the coefficients to be biased, possibly above or below the true of population variance.
[src:garch-models/heteroscedasticity] Thus, regression analysis using heteroscedastic data will still provide an unbiased estimate for the relationship between the predictor variable and the outcome, but standard errors and therefore inferences obtained from data analysis are suspect.
[src:garch-models/heteroscedasticity] Biased standard errors lead to biased inference, so results of hypothesis tests are possibly wrong.
[src:garch-models/heteroscedasticity] For example, if OLS is performed on a heteroscedastic data set, yielding biased standard error estimation, a researcher might fail to reject a null hypothesis at a given significance level, when that null hypothesis was actually uncharacteristic of the actual population (making a type II error).
[src:garch-models/heteroscedasticity] Under certain assumptions, the OLS estimator has a normal asymptotic distribution when properly normalized and centered (even when the data does not come from a normal distribution).
[src:garch-models/heteroscedasticity] This result is used to justify using a normal distribution, or a chi square distribution (depending on how the test statistic is calculated), when conducting a hypothesis test.
[src:garch-models/heteroscedasticity] This holds even under heteroscedasticity.
[src:garch-models/heteroscedasticity] More precisely, the OLS estimator in the presence of heteroscedasticity is asymptotically normal, when properly normalized and centered, with a variance-covariance matrix that differs from the case of homoscedasticity.
[src:garch-models/heteroscedasticity] In 1980, White proposed a consistent estimator for the variance-covariance matrix of the asymptotic distribution of the OLS estimator.
[src:garch-models/heteroscedasticity] This validates the use of hypothesis testing using OLS estimators and White's variance-covariance estimator under heteroscedasticity.
[src:garch-models/heteroscedasticity] Heteroscedasticity is also a major practical issue encountered in ANOVA problems.
[src:garch-models/heteroscedasticity] The F test can still be used in some circumstances.
[src:garch-models/heteroscedasticity] However, it has been said that students in econometrics should not overreact to heteroscedasticity.
[src:garch-models/heteroscedasticity] Yet, in the context of binary choice models (Logit or Probit), heteroscedasticity will only result in a positive scaling effect on the asymptotic mean of the misspecified MLE (i.e. the model that ignores heteroscedasticity).
[src:garch-models/heteroscedasticity] As a result, the predictions which are based on the misspecified MLE will remain correct.
[src:garch-models/heteroscedasticity] In addition, the misspecified Probit and Logit MLE will be asymptotically normally distributed which allows performing the usual significance tests (with the appropriate variance-covariance matrix).
[src:garch-models/heteroscedasticity] However, regarding the general hypothesis testing, as pointed out by Greene, "simply computing a robust covariance matrix for an otherwise inconsistent estimator does not give it redemption.
[src:garch-models/heteroscedasticity] There are several common corrections for heteroscedasticity.
[src:garch-models/heteroscedasticity] Residuals can be tested for homoscedasticity using the Breusch–Pagan test, which performs an auxiliary regression of the squared residuals on the independent variables.
[src:garch-models/heteroscedasticity] From this auxiliary regression, the explained sum of squares is retained, divided by two, and then becomes the test statistic for a chi-squared distribution with the degrees of freedom equal to the number of independent variables.
[src:garch-models/heteroscedasticity] The null hypothesis of this chi-squared test is homoscedasticity, and the alternative hypothesis would indicate heteroscedasticity.
[src:garch-models/heteroscedasticity] Since the Breusch–Pagan test is sensitive to departures from normality or small sample sizes, the Koenker–Bassett or 'generalized Breusch–Pagan' test is commonly used instead.
[src:garch-models/heteroscedasticity] From the auxiliary regression, it retains the R-squared value which is then multiplied by the sample size, and then becomes the test statistic for a chi-squared distribution (and uses the same degrees of freedom).
[src:garch-models/heteroscedasticity] Although it is not necessary for the Koenker–Bassett test, the Breusch–Pagan test requires that the squared residuals also be divided by the residual sum of squares divided by the sample size.
[src:garch-models/heteroscedasticity] Testing for groupwise heteroscedasticity can be done with the Goldfeld–Quandt test.
[src:garch-models/heteroscedasticity] Due to the standard use of heteroskedasticity-consistent Standard Errors and the problem of Pre-test, econometricians nowadays rarely use tests for conditional heteroskedasticity.
[src:garch-models/heteroscedasticity] Although tests for heteroscedasticity between groups can formally be considered as a special case of testing within regression models, some tests have structures specific to this case.
[src:garch-models/heteroscedasticity] Two or more normal distributions, $N(\mu _{1},\Sigma _{1}),N(\mu _{2},\Sigma _{2}),$ are both homoscedastic and lack serial correlation if they share the same diagonals in their covariance matrix, $\Sigma _{1}{ii}=\Sigma _{2}{jj},\ \forall i=j.$ and their non-diagonal entries are zero.
[src:garch-models/heteroscedasticity] Homoscedastic distributions are especially useful to derive statistical pattern recognition and machine learning algorithms.
[src:garch-models/heteroscedasticity] One popular example of an algorithm that assumes homoscedasticity is Fisher's linear discriminant analysis.
[src:garch-models/heteroscedasticity] The concept of homoscedasticity can be applied to distributions on spheres.
[src:garch-models/heteroscedasticity] The study of homescedasticity and heteroscedasticity has been generalized to the multivariate case, which deals with the covariances of vector observations instead of the variance of scalar observations.
[src:garch-models/heteroscedasticity] One version of this is to use covariance matrices as the multivariate measure of dispersion.
[src:garch-models/heteroscedasticity] Several authors have considered tests in this context, for both regression and grouped-data situations.
[src:garch-models/heteroscedasticity] Bartlett's test for heteroscedasticity between grouped data, used most commonly in the univariate case, has also been extended for the multivariate case, but a tractable solution only exists for 2 groups.
[src:garch-models/heteroscedasticity] Approximations exist for more than two groups, and they are both called Box's M test.
[src:garch-models/stationary-process] In mathematics and statistics, a **stationary process** (also called a **strict/strictly stationary process** or **strong/strongly stationary process**) is a stochastic process whose statistical properties, such as mean and variance, do not change over time.
[src:garch-models/stationary-process] More formally, the joint probability distribution of the process remains the same when shifted in time.
[src:garch-models/stationary-process] This implies that the process is statistically consistent across different time periods.
[src:garch-models/stationary-process] Because many statistical procedures in time series analysis assume stationarity, non-stationary data are frequently transformed to achieve stationarity before analysis.
[src:garch-models/stationary-process] A common cause of non-stationarity is a trend in the mean, which can be due to either a unit root or a deterministic trend.
[src:garch-models/stationary-process] In the case of a unit root, stochastic shocks have permanent effects, and the process is not mean-reverting.
[src:garch-models/stationary-process] With a deterministic trend, the process is called trend-stationary, and shocks have only transitory effects, with the variable tending towards a deterministically evolving mean.
[src:garch-models/stationary-process] A trend-stationary process is not strictly stationary but can be made stationary by removing the trend.
[src:garch-models/stationary-process] Similarly, processes with unit roots can be made stationary through differencing.
[src:garch-models/stationary-process] Another type of non-stationary process, distinct from those with trends, is a cyclostationary process, which exhibits cyclical variations over time.
[src:garch-models/stationary-process] Strict stationarity, as defined above, can be too restrictive for many applications.
[src:garch-models/stationary-process] Therefore, other forms of stationarity, such as **wide-sense stationarity** or **⁠ N ⁠th-order stationarity**, are often used.
[src:garch-models/stationary-process] The definitions for different kinds of stationarity are not consistent among different authors (see Other terminology).
[src:garch-models/stationary-process] Since $\tau$ does not affect ⁠ $F_{X}(\cdot )$ ⁠, $F_{X}$ is independent of time.
[src:garch-models/stationary-process] White noise is the simplest example of a stationary process.
[src:garch-models/stationary-process] An example of a discrete-time stationary process where the sample space is also discrete (so that the random variable may take one of ⁠ N ⁠ possible values) is a Bernoulli scheme.
[src:garch-models/stationary-process] Other examples of a discrete-time stationary process with continuous sample space include some autoregressive and moving average processes that are both subsets of the autoregressive moving average model.
[src:garch-models/stationary-process] Models with a non-trivial autoregressive component may be either stationary or non-stationary, depending on the parameter values, and important non-stationary special cases are where unit roots exist in the model.
[src:garch-models/stationary-process] Then $\left\{X_{t}\right\}$ is a stationary time series, for which realisations consist of a series of constant values, with a different constant value for each realisation.
[src:garch-models/stationary-process] A law of large numbers does not apply on this case, as the limiting value of an average from a single realisation takes the random value determined by ⁠ Y ⁠, rather than taking the expected value of ⁠ Y ⁠.
[src:garch-models/stationary-process] The time average of $X_{t}$ does not converge since the process is not ergodic.
[src:garch-models/stationary-process] Then $\left\{X_{t}\right\}$ is strictly stationary since (⁠ $(t+Y)$ ⁠ modulo ⁠ $2\pi$ ⁠) follows the same uniform distribution as Y for any ⁠ t ⁠.
[src:garch-models/stationary-process] Keep in mind that a weakly white noise is not necessarily strictly stationary.
[src:garch-models/stationary-process] So $\{z_{t}\}$ is a white noise in the weak sense (the mean and cross-covariances are zero, and the variances are all the same), however it is not strictly stationary.
[src:garch-models/stationary-process] In **Eq.1**, the distribution of n samples of the stochastic process must be equal to the distribution of the samples shifted in time *for all* ⁠ n ⁠. ⁠ N ⁠th-order stationarity is a weaker form of stationarity where this is only requested for all n up to a certain order ⁠ N ⁠.
[src:garch-models/stationary-process] A weaker form of stationarity commonly employed in signal processing is known as **weak-sense stationarity**, **wide-sense stationarity (WSS)**, or **covariance stationarity**.
[src:garch-models/stationary-process] WSS random processes only require that 1st moment (i.e. the mean) and autocovariance do not vary with respect to time and that the 2nd moment is finite for all times.
[src:garch-models/stationary-process] Any strictly stationary process that has a finite mean and covariance is also WSS.
[src:garch-models/stationary-process] The first property implies that the mean function $m_{X}(t)$ must be constant.
[src:garch-models/stationary-process] The second property implies that the autocovariance function depends only on the *difference* between $t_{1}$ and $t_{2}$ and only needs to be indexed by one variable rather than two variables.
[src:garch-models/stationary-process] The third property says that the second moments must be finite for any time ⁠ t ⁠.
[src:garch-models/stationary-process] The main advantage of wide-sense stationarity is that it places the time-series in the context of Hilbert spaces.
[src:garch-models/stationary-process] Let ⁠ H ⁠ be the Hilbert space generated by ⁠ $\{x(t)\}$ ⁠ (that is, the closure of the set of all linear combinations of these random variables in the Hilbert space of all square-integrable random variables on the given probability space).
[src:garch-models/stationary-process] By the positive definiteness of the autocovariance function, it follows from Bochner's theorem that there exists a positive measure $\mu$ on the real line such that ⁠ H ⁠ is isomorphic to the Hilbert subspace of ⁠ $L^{2}(\mu )$ ⁠ generated by ⁠ $\{e^{-2\pi i\xi \cdot t}\}$ ⁠.
[src:garch-models/stationary-process] where the integral on the right-hand side is interpreted in a suitable (Riemann) sense.
[src:garch-models/stationary-process] The same result holds for a discrete-time stationary process, with the spectral measure now defined on the unit circle.
[src:garch-models/stationary-process] When processing WSS random signals with linear, time-invariant (LTI) filters, it is helpful to think of the correlation function as a linear operator.
[src:garch-models/stationary-process] Since it is a circulant operator (depends only on the difference between the two arguments), its eigenfunctions are the Fourier complex exponentials.
[src:garch-models/stationary-process] Additionally, since the eigenfunctions of LTI operators are also complex exponentials, LTI processing of WSS random signals is highly tractable—all computations can be performed in the frequency domain.
[src:garch-models/stationary-process] Thus, the WSS assumption is widely employed in signal processing algorithms.
[src:garch-models/stationary-process] The concept of stationarity may be extended to two stochastic processes.
[src:garch-models/stationary-process] The terminology used for types of stationarity other than strict stationarity can be rather mixed.
[src:garch-models/stationary-process] In time series analysis and stochastic processes, stationarizing a time series is a crucial preprocessing step aimed at transforming a non-stationary process into a stationary one.
[src:garch-models/stationary-process] Several techniques exist for achieving this, depending on the type and order of non-stationarity present.
[src:garch-models/stationary-process] For first-order non-stationarity, where the mean of the process varies over time, differencing is a common and effective method: it transforms the series by subtracting each value from its predecessor, thus stabilizing the mean.
[src:garch-models/stationary-process] For non-stationarities up to the second order, time-frequency analysis (e.g., Wavelet transform, Wigner distribution function, or Short-time Fourier transform) can be employed to isolate and suppress time-localized, nonstationary spectral components.
[src:garch-models/stationary-process] Additionally, surrogate data methods can be used to construct strictly stationary versions of the original time series.
[src:garch-models/stationary-process] One of the ways for identifying non-stationary times series is the ACF plot.
[src:garch-models/stationary-process] Sometimes, patterns will be more visible in the ACF plot than in the original time series; however, this is not always the case.
[src:garch-models/stationary-process] The choice of method for time series stationarization depends on the nature of the non-stationarity and the goals of the analysis, especially when building models that require strict stationarity assumptions, such as ARMA or spectral-based techniques.
[src:garch-models/stationary-process] More details on some time series stationarization methods are presented below.
[src:garch-models/stationary-process] One way to make some time series first-order stationary is to compute the differences between consecutive observations.
[src:garch-models/stationary-process] Differencing can help stabilize the mean of a time series by removing changes in the level of a time series, and so eliminating trends.
[src:garch-models/stationary-process] This can also remove seasonality, if differences are taken appropriately (e.g. differencing observations 1 year apart to remove a yearly trend).
[src:garch-models/stationary-process] Transformations such as logarithms can help to stabilize the variance of a time series.
[src:garch-models/stationary-process] The surrogate method for stationarization works by generating a new time series that preserves certain statistical properties of the original series while removing its nonstationary components.
[src:garch-models/stationary-process] A common approach is to apply the Fourier Transform to the original time series to obtain its magnitude and phase spectra.
[src:garch-models/stationary-process] The magnitude spectrum, which determines the power distribution across frequencies, is retained to preserve the global autocorrelation structure.
[src:garch-models/stationary-process] Applying the inverse Fourier Transform to the modified spectra yields a strictly stationary surrogate time series: one with the same power spectrum as the original but lacking the temporal structures that caused non-stationarity.
[src:garch-models/stationary-process] This technique is often used in hypothesis tests for probing the stationarity property.
[src:garch-models/volatility-finance] In finance, **volatility** (usually denoted by "σ") is the degree of variation of a trading price series over time, usually measured by the standard deviation of logarithmic returns.
[src:garch-models/volatility-finance] Historic volatility measures a time series of past market prices.
[src:garch-models/volatility-finance] Implied volatility looks forward in time, being derived from the market price of a market-traded derivative (in particular, an option).
[src:garch-models/volatility-finance] For a financial instrument whose price follows a Gaussian random walk, or Wiener process, the width of the distribution increases as time increases.
[src:garch-models/volatility-finance] This is because there is an increasing probability that the instrument's price will be farther away from the initial price as time increases.
[src:garch-models/volatility-finance] However, rather than increase linearly, the volatility increases with the square-root of time as time increases, because some fluctuations are expected to cancel each other out, so the most likely deviation after twice the time will not be twice the distance from zero.
[src:garch-models/volatility-finance] Since observed price changes do not follow Gaussian distributions, others such as the Lévy distribution are often used.
[src:garch-models/volatility-finance] These can capture attributes such as "fat tails".
[src:garch-models/volatility-finance] Volatility is a statistical measure of dispersion around the average of any random variable such as market parameters etc.
[src:garch-models/volatility-finance] For any fund that evolves randomly with time, volatility is defined as the standard deviation of a sequence of random variables, each of which is the return of the fund over some corresponding sequence of (equally sized) times.
[src:garch-models/volatility-finance] Thus, "annualized" volatility *σ*annually is the standard deviation of an instrument's yearly logarithmic returns.
[src:garch-models/volatility-finance] A common assumption is that *P* = 252 trading days in any given year.
[src:garch-models/volatility-finance] The formulas used above to convert returns or volatility measures from one time period to another assume a particular underlying model or process.
[src:garch-models/volatility-finance] These formulas are accurate extrapolations of a random walk, or Wiener process, whose steps have finite variance.
[src:garch-models/volatility-finance] However, more generally, for natural stochastic processes, the precise relationship between volatility measures for different time periods is more complicated.
[src:garch-models/volatility-finance] If *α* = 2 the Wiener process scaling relation is obtained, but some people believe *α* < 2 for financial activities such as stocks, indexes and so on.
[src:garch-models/volatility-finance] This was discovered by Benoît Mandelbrot, who looked at cotton prices and found that they followed a Lévy alpha-stable distribution with *α* = 1.7.
[src:garch-models/volatility-finance] Much research has been devoted to modelling and forecasting the volatility of financial returns, and yet few theoretical models explain how volatility comes to exist in the first place.
[src:garch-models/volatility-finance] Roll (1984) shows that volatility is affected by market microstructure.
[src:garch-models/volatility-finance] Glosten and Milgrom (1985) shows that at least one source of volatility can be explained by the liquidity provision process.
[src:garch-models/volatility-finance] When market makers infer the possibility of adverse selection, they adjust their trading ranges, which in turn increases the band of price oscillation.
[src:garch-models/volatility-finance] In September 2019, JPMorgan Chase determined the effect of US President Donald Trump's tweets, and called it the Volfefe index combining volatility and the covfefe meme.
[src:garch-models/volatility-finance] Volatility affects pricing of options, being a parameter of the Black–Scholes model.
[src:garch-models/volatility-finance] Volatility does not measure the direction of price changes, merely their dispersion.
[src:garch-models/volatility-finance] This is because when calculating standard deviation (or variance), all differences are squared, so that negative and positive differences are combined into one quantity.
[src:garch-models/volatility-finance] Two instruments with different volatilities may have the same expected return, but the instrument with higher volatility will have larger swings in values over a given period of time.
[src:garch-models/volatility-finance] For example, a lower volatility stock may have an expected (average) return of 7%, with annual volatility of 5%.
[src:garch-models/volatility-finance] Ignoring compounding effects, this would indicate returns from approximately negative 3% to positive 17% most of the time (19 times out of 20, or 95% via a two standard deviation rule).
[src:garch-models/volatility-finance] A higher volatility stock, with the same expected return of 7% but with annual volatility of 20%, would indicate returns from approximately negative 33% to positive 47% most of the time (19 times out of 20, or 95%).
[src:garch-models/volatility-finance] These estimates assume a normal distribution; in reality stock price movements are found to be leptokurtotic (fat-tailed).
[src:garch-models/volatility-finance] Although the Black-Scholes equation assumes predictable constant volatility, this is not observed in real markets.
[src:garch-models/volatility-finance] Amongst more realistic models are Emanuel Derman and Iraj Kani's and Bruno Dupire's local volatility, Poisson process where volatility jumps to new levels with a predictable frequency, and the increasingly popular Heston model of stochastic volatility.
[src:garch-models/volatility-finance] It is common knowledge that many types of assets experience periods of high and low volatility.
[src:garch-models/volatility-finance] That is, during some periods, prices go up and down quickly, while during other times they barely move at all.
[src:garch-models/volatility-finance] In foreign exchange market, price changes are seasonally heteroskedastic with periods of one day and one week.
[src:garch-models/volatility-finance] Periods when prices fall quickly (a crash) are often followed by prices going down even more, or going up by an unusual amount.
[src:garch-models/volatility-finance] Also, a time when prices rise quickly (a possible bubble) may often be followed by prices going up even more, or going down by an unusual amount.
[src:garch-models/volatility-finance] Most typically, extreme movements do not appear 'out of nowhere'; they are presaged by larger movements than usual or by known uncertainty in specific future events.
[src:garch-models/volatility-finance] This is termed autoregressive conditional heteroskedasticity.
[src:garch-models/volatility-finance] Whether such large movements have the same direction, or the opposite, is more difficult to say.
[src:garch-models/volatility-finance] And an increase in volatility does not always presage a further increase—the volatility may simply go back down again.
[src:garch-models/volatility-finance] Measures of volatility depend not only on the period over which it is measured, but also on the selected time resolution, as the information flow between short-term and long-term traders is asymmetric.
[src:garch-models/volatility-finance] As a result, volatility measured with high resolution contains information that is not covered by low resolution volatility and vice versa.
[src:garch-models/volatility-finance] Some authors point out that realized volatility and implied volatility are backward and forward looking measures, and do not reflect current volatility.
[src:garch-models/volatility-finance] To address that issue an alternative, ensemble measures of volatility were suggested.
[src:garch-models/volatility-finance] One of the measures is defined as the standard deviation of ensemble returns instead of time series of returns.
[src:garch-models/volatility-finance] Another considers the regular sequence of directional-changes as the proxy for the instantaneous volatility.
[src:garch-models/volatility-finance] For instance, a company like Microsoft would have clean volatility caused by people buying and selling on a daily basis but dirty (or event volatility) events like quarterly earnings or a possibly anti-trust announcement.
[src:garch-models/volatility-finance] Breaking down volatility into two components is useful in order to accurately price how much an option is worth, especially when identifying what events may contribute to a swing.
[src:garch-models/volatility-finance] The job of fundamental analysts at market makers and option trading boutique firms typically entails trying to assign numeric values to these numbers.
[src:garch-models/volatility-finance] Using a simplification of the above formula it is possible to estimate annualized volatility based solely on approximate observations.
[src:garch-models/volatility-finance] Suppose you notice that a market price index, which has a current value near 10,000, has moved about 100 points a day, on average, for many days.
[src:garch-models/volatility-finance] This would constitute a 1% daily movement, up or down.
[src:garch-models/volatility-finance] To annualize this, you can use the "rule of 16", that is, multiply by 16 to get 16% as the annual volatility.
[src:garch-models/volatility-finance] The rationale for this is that 16 is the square root of 256, which is approximately the number of trading days in a year (252).
[src:garch-models/volatility-finance] This also uses the fact that the standard deviation of the sum of *n* independent variables (with equal standard deviations) is √n times the standard deviation of the individual variables.
[src:garch-models/volatility-finance] However importantly this does not capture (or in some cases may give excessive weight to) occasional large movements in market price which occur less frequently than once a year.
[src:garch-models/volatility-finance] The average magnitude of the observations is merely an approximation of the standard deviation of the market index.
[src:garch-models/volatility-finance] Assuming that the market index daily changes are normally distributed with mean zero and standard deviation *σ*, the expected value of the magnitude of the observations is √(2/π)*σ* = 0.798*σ*.
[src:garch-models/volatility-finance] The net effect is that this crude approach underestimates the true volatility by about 20%.
[src:garch-models/volatility-finance] Volatility thus mathematically represents a drag on the CAGR (formalized as the "volatility tax").
[src:garch-models/volatility-finance] Realistically, most financial assets have negative skewness and leptokurtosis, so this formula tends to be over-optimistic.
[src:garch-models/volatility-finance] for a rough estimate, where *k* is an empirical factor (typically five to ten).
[src:garch-models/volatility-finance] Despite the sophisticated composition of most volatility forecasting models, critics claim that their predictive power is similar to that of plain-vanilla measures, such as simple past volatility especially out-of-sample, where different data are used to estimate the models and to test them.
[src:garch-models/volatility-finance] Other works have agreed, but claim critics failed to correctly implement the more complicated models.
[src:garch-models/volatility-finance] Some practitioners and portfolio managers seem to completely ignore or dismiss volatility forecasting models.
[src:garch-models/volatility-finance] For example, Nassim Taleb famously titled one of his *Journal of Portfolio Management* papers "We Don't Quite Know What We are Talking About When We Talk About Volatility".
[src:garch-models/volatility-finance] In a similar note, Emanuel Derman expressed his disillusion with the enormous supply of empirical models unsupported by theory.
[src:garch-models/volatility-finance] He argues that, while "theories are attempts to uncover the hidden principles underpinning the world around us, as Albert Einstein did with his theory of relativity", we should remember that "models are metaphors – analogies that describe one thing relative to another".
[src:garch-models/volatility-finance] Machine learning and deep learning methods have also been applied to realized volatility forecasting.
